\<h2 id=3D\"Userdocument:Telepresenceworkflows-Introduction\"\>\<span
class=3D\"n=

h-number\"\>1.1. \</span\>\<span style=3D\"color:
rgb(34,34,34);\"\>Introduction\</s=

pan\>\</h2\>

\<p\>\<span style=3D\"color: rgb(34,34,34);\"\>Modern
microservices-based applica=

tions that are deployed into Kubernetes often consist of tens or
hundreds o=

f services. The resource constraints and a number of these services mean
th=

at it is often difficult or impossible to run all of this on a local
develo=

pment machine, which makes fast development and debugging very
challenging.=

\</span\>\</p\>

\<p\>\<a class=3D\"external-link\"
href=3D\"https://www.getambassador.io/docs/tel=

epresence\" rel=3D\"nofollow\"\>Telepresence \</a\>enables you to
connect your lo=

cal development machine seamlessly to the K8s cluster via a two-way
proxyin=

g mechanism. This enables you to code locally and run the majority of
your =

services within a K8s cluster.\</p\>

\<p\>This document provides walkthroughs to utilize telepresence in
local dev=

elopment.\</p\>

the K8s =

\<p\>Before we proceed let\'s take a look at some pre-requisites\</p\>

\<ol\>

\<li\>Telepresence can be used to intercept the traffic from the

pes of \<span class=3D\"inline-comment-marker\"

workloads/controllers/deployment/\"

workloads/controllers/statefulset/\"
rel=3D\"nofollow\"\>StatefulSet\</a\>\</li\>

href=3D\"https://k=

ubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/\"
rel=3D\"nofollow\"\>K=

8s service\</a\> associated with it (ClusterIP, NodePort,
LoadBalancer)\</li\>

\<li\>The current context in your config file in the .kube folder should
poin=

t to the K8s cluster where you want to use telepresence.\</li\>

\<li\>If you want to avoid downtime of the microservice you are trying

ercept, then make sure the code of the microservice is running on the
works=
